In the first step, Kaiser test confirmed the successful conversion of the primary amino groups into carboxylic acids through the decreased number of amino groups (100 µmol g−1) as compared to the pristine material (1350 µmol g−1). In addition, the FT-IR spectrum of CDs-COOH showed an increased intensity of the peaks typical of C = O bonds (1649 and 1701 cm−1) compared to the bare CDs, [39] and the appearance of a signal at 1368 cm−1 attribute to the symmetric stretching of the carboxylate group (
                           Fig. S1
                        ).

The successful coupling reaction forming CDs-Crown was then confirmed by FT-IR spectroscopy. The FT-IR spectrum of CDs-Crown showed the typical signatures of both nanodots and crown,[40] but an increased intensity of the amide stretching (1651 cm−1) as a result of the functionalization reaction (
                           Fig. S2
                        ).

The coupling was further characterized by optical spectroscopy techniques.[39] The UV–Vis spectrum in water of CDs-Crown showed an absorption peak at 260 nm, which is ascribed to the π-π* transition of the conjugated C = C units from the carbon core of the nanoparticle (
                           Fig. S3
                        ) [39]. A blue shift of the absorption band at 286 nm, corresponding to the π-π* transition of CDs, was detected as a result of the presence of the crown. More importantly, the FL emission spectrum of CDs-Crown in water showed the typical CDs excitation wavelength dependence with no evident quenching, which is important to exploit the hybrid material for FL sensing (Fig. 2
                        ) [6,39].
